[3]
Date: Wed, 18 Jan 2006
From: Nick Honhold <nick@plewland.demon.co.uk> [edited]

I have some questions about H5N1 HPAI that I hope others might find
interesting and respond to.
1) Does anyone have any information about the time from infection to the
start of shedding of the virus compared to the onset of clinical signs and
increased mortality? This is an important point for undertaking both
forward and backward tracings and knowing how much spread there might have
been before an outbreak is detected. I realise that it will be variable
both in general and perhaps between different species, but I think a
ballpark figure would help. This period of "silent spread" is critical to
the size of outbreaks. So far I haven't been able to find much information
on how long this period is for HPAI in general, let alone H5N1.
2) Vaccination of poultry is being used in various countries. I can see how
this will work in large-scale commercial farms, especially when these are
all-in, all-out single-age sites; each batch can be vaccinated at birth or
some other life stage. But my experience of village poultry is that they
are multi-age and that there is a very rapid turnover in the population
(over 100 per cent per year, or around 10 per cent per month in my
experience), which would suggest a rapidly waning flock immunity.
For vaccination to work in that sort of situation, a one-off vaccination
campaign is rarely effective; it is usually necessary to have constant
supplies of vaccine available for administration when required. Am I right
about this and is it achievable?
3) A lot of disease is being found in areas where migratory wildfowl either
pass through or over-winter. I wonder if most outbreaks are being found in
these areas because that is where surveillance is being concentrated,
rather than because that is the only place where the virus is present.
Might the example of the recent outbreaks in Turkey suggest that widespread
surveillance is required, not so focused on wildfowl? I want to emphasise
that I intend absolutely no criticism of the Turkish veterinary services
when I say that -- quite the opposite; I have a lot of sympathy for the
very difficult situation they have been faced with.
--
Nick Honhold
<nick@plewland.demon.co.uk>
