[4]
Date: Wed, 18 Jan 2006
From: Ginger Switzer<EHPEC@comcast.net>

I believe I read H5N1 antibodies had been detected in pigs many months ago.
With all the bird monitoring going on, I wondered if anyone was monitoring
pigs or other animals that might be shedding virus without noticeable symptoms.
--
Ginger Switzer, ARNP, COHN-S
EHPEC Employee Health Practitioners, Educators, and Consultants
<EHPEC@comcast.net>
[Responses to the above queries, from first-hand sources, are welcome.
The following additional information from Romania and Georgia is added:
1. Romania:
On 17 Jan 2006, Romania notified the OIE on 2 new outbreaks of H5, in
Braila County: one in the village of Ciresu, the other one in the village
of Dudesti. Reportedly, both outbreaks started on 10 Jan 2006.(see
<http://oie.int/downld/AVIAN%20INFLUENZA/Romania%20Follow%20up%20report%20060117.pdf>).
The following control measures have reportedly been applied in both
affected localities since 13 Jan 2006:
- partial stamping-out, in the infected premises and in neighbouring
backyard premises (there were 6 premises in Dudesti where 127 fowls were
culled and 10 premises in Ciresu where 157 fowls have been culled);
- movement control measures, applied to people and to animals (poultry,
poultry products, feed, etc);
- disinfection of backyard premises in the locality;
- sanitary checkpoints ("filters") installed at the entrance of the localities.
- destruction of carcasses, assured by burning and burying.
2. Georgia:
Mikheil Svimonishvili, Georgian agriculture minister, stated on 18 Jan 2006
that the fact that the bird flu has not been detected after examination of
385 dead hens is not an argument for serenity. - Mod.AS]
